07309nam a22009495i 9781478022664DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780226647 a10.1515/97814780226642doi  a(DE-B1597)624494  a(OCoLC)1292600994  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGF75b.K55 2022 7aSOC0620002bisacsh04a304.2/8223/eng/2021100800aKin :bThinking with Deborah Bird Rose /ced. by Thom van Dooren, Matthew Chrulew. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (247 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tWorlds of Kin: An Introduction -- tONE The Sociality of Birds: Reflections on Ontological Edge Effects -- tTWO Loving the Difficult: Scotch Broom -- tTHREE Awakening to the Call of Others: What I Learned from Existential Ecology -- tFOUR Speculative Fabulations for Technoculture’s Generations: Taking Care of Unexpected Country -- tFIVE The Disappearing Snails of Hawai‘i: Storytelling for a Time of Extinctions -- tSIX Roadkill: Multispecies Mobility and Everyday Ecocide -- tSEVEN After Nature: Totemism Revisited -- tEIGHT Telling One’s Story in the Hearing of Buffalo: Liturgical Interventions from Beyond the Year Zero -- tNINE Ending with the Wind, Crying the Dawn -- tTEN Animality and the Life of the Spirit -- tELEVEN Life Is a Woven Basket of Relations -- tAfterword: Memories with Deborah Rose -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors to Kin draw on the work of anthropologist Deborah Bird Rose (1946–2018), a foundational voice in environmental humanities, to examine the relationships of interdependence and obligation between human and nonhuman lives. Through a close engagement over many decades with the Aboriginal communities of Yarralin and Lingara in northern Australia, Rose’s work explored possibilities for entangled forms of social and environmental justice. She sought to bring the insights of her Indigenous teachers into dialogue with the humanities and the natural sciences to describe and passionately advocate for a world of kin grounded in a profound sense of the connectivities and relationships that hold us together. Kin’s contributors take up Rose’s conceptual frameworks, often pushing academic fields beyond their traditional objects and methods of study. Together, the essays do more than pay tribute to Rose’s scholarship; they extend her ideas and underscore her ongoing critical and ethical relevance for a world still enduring and resisting ecocide and genocide.Contributors. The Bawaka Collective, Matthew Chrulew, Colin Dayan, Linda Payi Ford, Donna Haraway, James Hatley, Owain Jones, Stephen Muecke, Kate Rigby, Catriona (Cate) Sandilands, Isabelle Stengers, Anna Tsing, Thom van Dooren, Kate Wright  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEnvironmental ethics. 0aEthnoecology. 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aHuman geography. 0aHuman-animal relationships. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aBurarrwanga, Laklak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrulew, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrulew, Matthew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDayan, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDooren, Thom van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanambarr, Banbapuy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanambarr, Ritjilili, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanambarr-Stubbs, Merrkiyawuy, econtributor.4ctb4ht